observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to observe timeliness in the remittance of the provincial share of the SEF collection which is within 15 days of every succeeding month and to revisit RA No. 5447 to familiarize herself with the duties and responsibilities in the handling of SEF collections; 

Consider as a priority project, the linking of electronic systems between the Municipal Treasurer’s Office and the Municipal Accounting Office, not only to address the delayed remittance of SEF shares to the provincial government but the ultimate goal is to improve efficiency in revenue generation and financial reporting system of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive of the Municipality direct the responsible officials of the Municipality to:

Complete the annual physical inventory of the Property, Plant and Equipment;

Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) for PPE;

Conduct reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the accounting records; and

Submit the RPCPPE to COA not later than January 31 of each year.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
Establish a Municipal Inventory Committee whose members shall have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Units of the Local Government Unit (LGU), who shall be responsible for the Annual Inventory Count and reconciliation of records to establish the existence, completeness and condition of all PPEs owned by the Municipality;
Enjoin the officers/personnel involved to be guided with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 re: Guidelines in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station and Disposition for Non-Existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies, as transmitted through our letter dated 24 November 2021;
Enforce strict observance by the personnel involved on the deadlines in the submission of the RPCPPE required under Section 124 of the NGAS Manual; and
The Municipal Accounting Office to maintain a Lapsing Schedule for PPE to facilitate the preparation of the monthly depreciation expense during the year.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to direct:

Acting Municipal Treasurer to open a new bank account necessary to facilitate the creation of SAGF where the remaining balance of the BGCM can be segregated and deposited;

Municipal Accounting Office to create and maintain a Special Account in the General Fund solely for the Bayanihan Grant to aid in the easy monitoring of utilization of the fund in compliance to DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125;

Henceforth, comply with the requirements of laws, rules and regulations to support the National Government’s effort towards a unified, cohesive and orderly implementation of the national policy to address COVID-19.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:

Create a team or committee to handle the processing/release of evaluation results from the Bureau of Mines and Geo-Science Bureau to determine whether or not the identified area can pass the required standards and requirements;

Intensify the on-going negotiation with the lot owner intended for the Construction/Rehabilitation of PWS to avoid further price increases;

Make negotiations with adjacent lot owners for the Tourism Development Program. Request for their support and participation to the program by instilling into their minds the good intentions of the government to promote the tourism industry of the municipality;

Provide additional funding to acquire the needed Technical and Scientific Equipment, if it warrants; and

